Deploying a WordPress Server Choose a blueprint. Click on the Home button in the top banner and select Create instance. Ensure that the location of the virtual machine (instance) matches the database you&rsquo;ve recently deployed. If it defaults to a different location or AZ, click &ldquo;Change AWS Region and Availability Zone&rdquo; and select the correct value. Please select your instance image. Under &ldquo;Select a blueprint,&rdquo; click on OS Only and choose Ubuntu 20.04 LTS. Click on &ldquo;Add launch script.&rdquo;
You will use the launch script to install prerequisites, as well as WordPress and WordPress CLI. Paste the following code into the launch script: # Update the package indexsudo apt update# Install the common packagesudo apt install software-properties-common -y# Add the PHP repository to the instancesudo add-apt-repository ppa:ondrej/php -y# Update the package index now that the new repository has been addedsudo apt update# Install Apache, PHP, mysql clientsudo apt-get install apache2 php8.0 libapache2-mod-php8.0 php8.0-common php8.0-imap php8.0-mbstring php8.0-xmlrpc php8.0-soap php8.0-gd php8.0-xml php8.0-intl php8.0-mysql php8.0-cli php8.0-bcmath php8.0-ldap php8.0-zip php8.0-curl mysql-client-core-8.0 -y# Go to the web foldercd /var/www/html/# Download the latest version of WordPresssudo curl -O https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz# Unzip the filessudo tar xzvf latest.tar.gz# Delete the zipped downloadsudo rm ./latest.tar.gz# Move all the WordPress files to the root web directorycd ./wordpress/ &amp;&amp; sudo mv ./* ../# Create the WordPress Config file from the samplesudo cp /var/www/html/wp-config-sample.php /var/www/html/wp-config.php# Change the permissions for the directorysudo chown -R www-data /var/www# Remove the sample config filesudo rm /var/www/html/wp-config-sample.php# Go back up a level and delete index.htmlcd ../sudo rm ./index.html# Download WP-CLIsudo curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wp-cli/builds/gh-pages/phar/wp-cli.phar# Make it executablesudo chmod +x wp-cli.phar# Move it to the bin directorysudo mv wp-cli.phar /usr/local/bin/wp# Create the wp-cli config file that points to our WordPress folderecho &#34;path: /var/www/html&#34; &gt; $HOME/wp-cli.yml# Enable the GD PHP extension by removing the &#39;;&#39;sudo sed -i &#39;s/;extension=gd/extension=gd/&#39; /etc/php/8.0/apache2/php.ini# Restart the apache servicesudo /etc/init.d/apache2 restart Scroll down to &lsquo;Choose your instance plan.&rsquo;
Select the &lsquo;$5 USD&rsquo; server with 1GB of memory and 1 vCPU. Define your instance We need to name your virtual machine.
Name your instance &lsquo;Workshop-WordPress&rsquo;.
Click Create instance.

To clean up this lab, please follow these steps:
Click on the &ldquo;Instances&rdquo; tab. For each of the 3 virtual machines, click the three dots button, then click &ldquo;Delete,&rdquo; and confirm the deletion by clicking &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; Do this for all virtual machines created for this lab.
Click on the &ldquo;Databases&rdquo; tab. Click the three dots next to &ldquo;Workshop-DB-Instance,&rdquo; then click &ldquo;Delete,&rdquo; and confirm the deletion by clicking &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
Click on the &ldquo;Networking&rdquo; tab. For each static IP address you created in this lab, click the three dots button, then click &ldquo;Delete,&rdquo; and confirm the deletion by clicking &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
Click on the &ldquo;Snapshots&rdquo; tab. For each snapshot you created in this lab, open the &ldquo;Instance snapshot&rdquo; dropdown, click the three dots button, then click &ldquo;Delete snapshot.&rdquo; Then, click &ldquo;Yes&rdquo; to confirm the deletion.
At this point, your Lightsail dashboard should be empty of resources. If you still have resources running in the dashboard, ensure they were deployed in this lab, then follow the steps above to delete them.
